Web of Science revealed 132 outputs with the key words ‘termite’ and either ‘sustainable’ or ‘sustainability’ but among the outputs, only 71 were identified as research articles (see the list in the complementary file). Moreover, of these 71 outputs, 31% were published in the last two years (from 2017 onward), showing how recent this field of investigation is. The bibliometric map of these 71 articles shows that a large proportion addresses the pest status of termites (46%), which impacts SDGs 1 and 2 (no poverty and zero hunger) and 3 (good health and well-being) (Figure 2
                     ). Harmful impacts are associated with the consumption of lignocellulosic materials, reductions in crop yield and a degradation of constructions, leading to significant economic losses [4,5,12,14,15]. Although highly variable and context dependent, the rule seems to be that termite impacts are most important when plants are in the early stage of growth, during drought or under other stresses [12,16••
                     ].

A second more dispersed cluster appears in Figure 2 around the beneficial impacts of termites. Beneficial impacts are associated with their significant role on soil functioning in tropical environments. From this viewpoint, termite foraging and construction activities are associated with the construction of galleries that increase water infiltration and soil fertility [16••
                     ,17,18••
                     ] and the production of mounds that can be used for growing vegetables, harvesting mushrooms or used as amendments to increase soil fertility [19••
                     ,20,21•
                     ,22–24]. In India, termite mound soil is also used in mixtures with organic residues to accelerate the production of compost and increase its quality, while it is used in small gaps to retain water and improve the soil moisture content profile in the ‘Zai’ system in northern Burkina Faso [16••
                     ]. Termite mounds are also considered accurate predictors of the presence of precious metals, such as gold, or the proximity of water sources in deeper soil layers [25•
                     ].

Although rarely considered, termites can also increase farmers’ incomes, health and food security [19••
                     ]. In India, termite swarming is used by farmers in weather forecasting [26]. The use of termites as food source is ancient [27] and explained by their great nutritional values for animals, including humans [19••
                     ,21•
                     ,26,28]. Termites are also used in traditional popular medicine [28–31]. Medicinal plants growing on termite mounds are used by local populations to cure several diseases [20,32]. Termite mound soil can also be used as a medicine [31,33] and its consumption has been described in various African ethnic groups [21•
                     ,31,34]. This practice is generally considered as an adaptive advantage with therapeutic values for self-medication and it has been reported to be common among pregnant women, although non-pregnant women may also consume termite mound clays whenever they feel weak [21•
                     ]. This consumption is explained by the enrichment of clay and salts (e.g. Ca and Mg) in termite mound soils that act as adsorbents of harmful bacteria and toxins such as alkaloids in plant foods. Finally, along with their consumption, termites are also sold as food and generate an income, thus contributing the whole economy of villages [35]. For instance, Macrotermes spp. are commonly consumed by villagers in Africa where their sale can lead to a significant income [21•
                     ] while winged termites are collected by forest tribes and sold to local markets in South India [30]. Moreover, the harvesting, preparation and selling of termites are dominated by women and children in Zimbabwe who earn independent incomes, thus tackling the gender-equality issue [29].

Although poorly or not taken into account in SDGs, termites can also play an important spiritual role. The close interaction between termite mounds and humans is evidenced by the very specific attention that rural populations pay to termite mounds. In Benin, ethnic groups use termite mounds in traditional rituals to drive out evil spirits and attract fortunes and for the scarification of children during the return ceremonies of their father's maternal family [4]. From South-East Asia to West Africa, mounds are commonly worshiped or protected by the population on the basis of spiritual beliefs. They have been the home of ancestors since the Iron Age [45] and are seen as entrances to the netherworld and sources of fertility [46••
                     ]. Termite mounds can host spirits in Thailand. Abandoned termite mounds can be occupied by animals that are worshiped in India (Figure 3
                     ), such as snakes which are associated with Shiva, one of the most important gods in Hinduism, or Nagesvara, the lord of the Naga demons or primordial snake, which is a personification of the cosmic dichotomy of being beneficent in representing fecundity and malevolent in threatening destruction and a return to chaos [45]. Another interesting spiritual role of termites is found in the story of Valmiki, who was previously a robber, a hunter and a murderer named Ratnakara. Later, Ratnakara met an important vedic sage, Narada Muni, who taught him meditation. After years of meditation, termites built their nest on Ratnakara, who was then buried alive, becoming Valmiki, the one born in a termite hill [46••
                     ]. Finally, Valmiki wrote the Ramayana, which is also one of the most important stories in Hinduism. One lesson that we can learn from this story is that termites, through their activities, are able to produce the best (i.e. the writing of the Ramayana or the provision of ES) from the worst (i.e. the crime or their impact as pests). In other words, termites show us that the best and worst are intertwined.

Does the harmful or dark side impact of termites prevail over their beneficial or bright side impact? The question remains open. In 1998, Mando and Van Rheenen [47] questioned whether termites have to be seen as enemies and/or friends, while in 2019, the French Academy of Agriculture questioned whether insects have to be considered ‘foes, friends or models’. If the bright and dark sides of termites have to be evaluated while designing and implementing suitable management strategies [48•
                     ], the parable of Valmiki reminds us that we also need the dark side of elements if we want their bright side. This complexity is perhaps never as well evidenced as in the article of Herrick et al. [49], who used the example of termites positively impacting water infiltration but reducing C stocks in soil. This complexity is also summarized in Figure 4
                     , which shows the interdependence between the need for termites to feed on organic matter and their impacts on SDGs or, in other words, that one cannot be obtained without the other and that to get the bright, we have to accept the dark.
